04448nam a22007575i 9781501720703DE-B159720190430100931.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190430s2018    nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017207037 a10.7591/97815017207032doi  a(DE-B1597)515174  a(OCoLC)1100440207  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aPA3015.R5bH372 1994 7aLIT0041902bisacsh 7aLIT0220002bisacsh 7aLIT0250502bisacsh04a880.9/3512201 aAustin, Norman, eauthor.10aHelen of Troy and Her Shameless Phantom /cNorman Austin. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©2008  a1 online resource   atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMyth and Poetics00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tForeword / rNagy, Gregory -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tPart I. The Traditional Helen -- t1. The Helen of the Iliad -- t2. Sappho's Helen and the Problem of the Text -- tPart II. The Revised Helen -- t3. The Helen of the Odyssey -- t4. Stesichorus and His Palinode -- t5. Herodotus and Helen in Egypt -- t6. Euripides' Helen: The Final Revision -- tGlossary of Greek Terms -- tBibliography -- tIndex  aLike the male heroes of epic poetry, Helen of Troy has been immortalized, but not for deeds of strength and honor; she is remembered as the beautiful woman who disgraced herself and betrayed her family and state. Norman Austin here surveys interpretations of Helen in Greek literature from the Homeric period through later antiquity. He looks most closely at a revisionist myth according to which Helen never sailed to Troy, but remained blameless, while a libertine phantom or ghost impersonated her at Troy. Comparing the functions of contradictory images of Helen, Austin helps to clarify the problematic relations between beauty and honor and between ugliness and shame in ancient Greece.Austin first discusses the canonical account of the Iliad and the Odyssey: Helen as the archetype of woman without shame. He next considers different versions of Helen in the Homeric tradition. Among these, he shows how Sappho presents Helen as an icon of absolute beauty while she defends her own preference of eros over honor and her choice of woman as the object of desire. Austin then turns to three major authors who repudiated the traditional Helen of Troy: the lyric poet Stesichorus and the dramatist Euripides, who embraced the alternative myth of Helen's phantom; and the historian Herodotus, who claimed to have found in Egypt a Helen story that dispenses with both Helen and the phantom. Austin maintains that the conflicting motives that prompted these writers to rehabilitate Helen led to further revisions of her image, though none have endured as a credible substitute for the Helen of epic tradition.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Apr 2019) 0aGreek literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aHelen of Troy (Greek mythology) in literature. 0aTrojan WarxLiterature and the war. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCOR eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066750940uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/9781501720703423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781501720703.jpg  a978-3-11-066750-9  COR eBook-Package 2000-2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_CL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_CL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG